Your Turn 2.1a

  • Navigate to Day 2/worksheets, and make a copy of the R script named dat2_leaflet_intro.R which you can work with.


Follow the code in this script to:

  1. Load packages we'll need (library()) and the data set from yesterday

  2. From "species", create a new column/variable 'species type' (Human, Domestic or Wildlife)

  3. create map_data — a dataframe consisting of 2014 data only

Data preparation

Creating a column/variable for 'species type'

# create variable for type of species
raw_data$species_type <- ifelse(raw_data$species == "human", "Human", NA)
raw_data$species_type[which(raw_data$species %in% c("dog", "cat"))] <- "Domestic"
raw_data$species_type[which(raw_data$species %in% c("jackal", "lion"))] <- "Wildlife"

table(raw_data$species, raw_data$species_type)
##         
##          Domestic Human Wildlife
##   cat         320     0        0
##   dog         727     0        0
##   human         0   164        0
##   jackal        0     0      230
##   lion          0     0      158

Data preparation

Subsetting to only include 2014

raw_data$date[1]
## [1] 2010-01-14
## 950 Levels: 2010-01-14 2010-01-16 2010-01-24 2010-01-25 ... 2014-12-30
raw_data$date[1] %>% substr(1, 4)
## [1] "2010"
map_data <- raw_data %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(year = substr(date, 1,4)) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(year == 2014)

Simple static maps

Map Basics

The simplest map of this data using base plot()

plot(map_data$y ~ map_data$x, asp = 1)

Shapefile data

A simple verion using ggplot() with points coloured by human population density

ggplot(data = map_data, aes(x = x, y = y, col = density)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4) + # makes points transparent
  coord_equal() # sets aspect ratio 1:1

Shapefile data

Reading in data from shape file and using and we can plot using base plotting function

# x = longitude and y = latitude
plot(region_shp)

Combining shapefile data and ggplot()

ggplot() requires things to be in dataframe format so we use fortify() from the ggplot2 package to convert into a dataframe.

region_shp$id <- rownames(region_shp@data)
region_shp_df <- fortify(region_shp, region = "id")
region_shp_df <- left_join(region_shp_df, region_shp@data, by = "id")

Shapefile data with ggplot()

Combine previous plot with shape file data outlining regions.

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = region_shp_df, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = "white", color = "black") +
  geom_point(data = map_data, aes(x = x, y = y), col = "dodgerblue") +
  coord_equal()

Shapefile data with ggplot()

Same plot with regions colored by human population density

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = region_shp_df, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = log(density)),
               color = "black") +
  geom_point(data = map_data, aes(x = x, y = y, col = I("red")), alpha = 0.4) +
  labs(fill = expression(paste("People per km"^2, " (log)", sep = ""))) +
  coord_equal()

ggmap and qmplot()

qmplot() is the ggmap package's version of ggplot2's ggplot()

Using I() prevents the plotting of a legend beside the map

qmplot(data = map_data, x = x, y = y, colour = I("red"),
       size = I(2), darken = .2, zoom = 4)
